                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d764">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00 Revolutions/362: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in El Salvador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MWJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McCafferty</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-11-23T16:00:00-06:00"
                            >November 23, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:43 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. I am reliably informed that 500 old rifles and 500,000 rounds of 11 and 7
                    millimeter ammunition are being furnished to the Honduran Government by the
                        <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Martinez</persName> regime to suppress the
                    revolution there. Planes of the Taca Company have been making two trips to San
                    Salvador daily to transport these arms. Although without foundation the general
                    impression here is that the Guatemalan Government has been aiding the rebels.
                    Repeated to Legations Tegucigalpa and Guatemala.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McCafferty</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
